A new paper reports that Latinos age at a slower rate than other ethnic groups. The study&nbsp;(&quot;An Epigenetic Clock Analysis of Race/Ethnicity, Sex, and Coronary Heart Disease&quot;),&nbsp;published in Genome Biology, may one day lead to novel approaches that help&nbsp;slow the aging process for everyone, according to&nbsp;lead author Steve Horvath, Ph.D., professor of human genetics at the David Geffen School of Medicine at UCLA. 

&quot;Latinos live longer than Caucasians, despite experiencing higher rates of diabetes and other diseases. Scientists refer to this as the 'Hispanic paradox,' &quot; said Dr. Horvath. &quot;Our study helps explain this by demonstrating that Latinos age more slowly at the molecular level.&quot; 

